<HEADLINE>
Third South Asian Wushu Championship opens in Bangladesh
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 23 (Xinhua)
</P>
<P>
The 3rd South Asian Wushu Championship opened on Wednesday at
Mirpur Indoor Stadium in Bangladesh's capital Dhaka with an entry
of 160 athletes, coaches, judges and sports officials from 6
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony of the three-day tournament, the largest
since the first championship in Nepal in 2002, was held Wednesday
morning with unique Bangladesh traditional dance performance.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh and Indian athletes also staged wushu demonstration
winning a huge wave of applause from the audiences.
</P>
<P>
"Wushu is not only a physical practice but also a good mental
state building. Now Wushu is a popular game in South Asia,"
Siddiqui, president of Bangladesh Wushu Association (BWUA), said
at the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He called for all the countries in the region to support wushu
development. He thanked Chinese Wushu Association and
International Wushu Federation for donating taolu mat and sanshou
platform for the championship.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yulong, vice president of Chinese Wushu Association, who
also presented the ceremony, spoke highly of the development of
wushu in South Asia as well as Southeast Asia. He appreciated the
efforts Bangladesh has made for the championship and wished the
championship to be very successful.
</P>
<P>
Athletes from Bangladesh, India, Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka and
Afghanistan will compete for 34 gold medals.
</P>
<P>
BWUA, the organizer of the championship, was founded in 1981 and
has 300 members around Bangladesh.
</P>
